3rd batch of home-visiting group of Japanese women in DPRK back 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;   Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- The third batch of home-visiting group of Japanese women residing in the DPRK today came back after visiting Japan under an agreement reached between the red cross organizations of the DPRK and Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The visiting group was greeted at the airport by Ho Hae Ryong, vice-chairman of the central committee of the Red Cross Society of the DPRK, officials concerned and their families and relatives.

Friendly meeting with Mongolian friendship delegation 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- A friendly meeting with members of a Mongolian friendship delegation was held by the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries yesterday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Invited to the meeting were members of the Mongolian friendship delegation headed by president CH. Batjargal of the Federation of Mongolian Peace and Friendship Organizations, Mongolian ambassador to Korea Damdiny Byamba and embassy officials. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Present were acting chairman Mun Jae Chol and vice-chairman Choe Jong Hwan of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries, and other officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   They saw an art performance given by schoolchildren's art circle members and talked about further developing the friendly relations between the two peoples.

Independence Day of Chile marked 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- A meeting was held in Pyongyang yesterday to mark the 190th anniversary of the Independence of Chile. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Present there were Kim Jin Bom, vice-chairman of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries and chairman of the Korean Association for Friendship with Latin American and Caribbean Region, members of the association and the Korea-Chile Friendship Association and working people in the city. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   A speech was made and a congratulatory message to the President of Chile was adopted at the meeting. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The participants looked round photos introducing Chile at the meeting place.

Int'l symposium on compound micro-organism technology and natural farming method 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- An international symposium on compound micro-organism technology and natural farming method is to be held in Pyongyang for three days from September 20. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Attending the symposium will be representatives from nearly 20 countries in different regions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The symposium will exchange successes and experience gained in the process of developing compound micro-organism technology in different regions and countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   It will inform the participants of how the compound micro-organism technology has been applied in the fields of agriculture, stock-breeding, fish-breeding  and environment purification and discuss the prospect of its development. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The symposium will also discuss scientific and technological issues concerning natural farming method (organic farming method).

KCNA on Ishihara's outbursts 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- Kinhide Mushakoji, director of the board of the International Institute of the Juche Idea, on a visit to Korea, said that his. Korea visit brought the validity and vitality of the Juche idea home to him. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  Saying that the Juche idea is being disseminated and studied on a worldwide scale, he noted that it is, indeed, the greatest guiding idea of the present times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He went on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Juche idea is the most correct guideline indicating the road that should be followed by progressive humankind. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   This great idea will remain forever a banner of sure victory on the road of the cause of independence.

Juche idea, greatest guiding idea 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- Tokyo Metropolitan Governor Ishihara reportedly let loose outbursts again to fan up militarism on Sept. 14. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He said that the "three principles of arms export" banning and restricting the arms export of Japan are "foolish rules," "it is a guarantee for security in different respects to sell arms and it is good for Japan to develop its own arms."&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Ishihara with militarism and ultra-nationalism imprinted in his mind criticized the "three principles of arms export" and insisted on the "justification" of arms export and laid stress on the development of ultra-modern weapons, which is not accidental. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   This indicates that the moves of the ultra-right wing forces of Japan and their political influence presented themselves in the political arena as the main source of actual threat which evokes serious apprehensions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Japanese authorities did not care a fig for the militarist outbursts of Ishihara and others, regarding them as an "expression of personal view" with no political and practical danger. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   As developments show, however, the embellishment of the history of the past aggression is now assuming official character along with the outbursts of Ishihara and arms buildup aiming to become a military giant is being stepped up as a policy in Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   These facts show that the blast of Ishihara is not a personal remark but represents the intention of the political forces who are hell bent on taking systematic and legal measures to legalize the militarism of Japan and formulates their immediate target. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Japanese reactionaries should act with discretion, mindful that their reckless militarist moves lead to destruction.

Moves of Japan Defense Agency to deploy F-2 fighters denounced 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- The Defense Agency of Japan decided to deploy F-2 support fighters, which may conduct aerial operations on the Korean peninsula, to the air "Self-Defense Force."&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Commenting on this decision, Rodong Sinmun today warns that if the Japanese reactionaries reinvade Korea at any cost, they will get nothing but ruin. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The news analyst goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   It is very dangerous that the Japanese reactionaries decided to deploy F-2 fighters after examining the plan for air raids on "a missile-launching site" in the DPRK by use of the planes. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   They are seeking to reinvade Korea, reiterating rapid and effective "countermeasures" in "emergencies in the areas surrounding Japan" including "an emergency on the Korean peninsula." Their moves are going beyond the limit line, assuming unprecedented nakedness and feasibility. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   What they intend is to make a forestalling attack on the DPRK by force of arms. Japan always says it hopes the relaxation of tension and peace on the Korean peninsula. It is a sheer lie and a camouflage to cover up its attempt to reinvade Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Japanese reactionaries' move to deploy F-2 support fighters focussing on the Korean peninsula is a danger signal of reinvasion. The Japanese militarists' reinvasion of Korea is a matter of time. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   But, we are not afraid of it. We are fully ready to counter any attack.

DPRK catches Olympic weightlifting silver medal 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- DPRK weightlifter Ri Song Hui won the silver medal in the women's 58kg division of weightlifting at the 27th Olympiad in Sidney on Sept. 18. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   She lifted a total of 220 kg (97.5 snatch and 122.5 jerk).

Japan warned to act with discretion 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;   Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- Minju Joson today in a signed commentary denounces Japan for conducting "keen activities" to use the UN Millennium Summit and the UN General Assembly session as a stage for realizing its political purpose. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Japanese Prime Minister at the UN Millennium Summit talked about Japan's "financial contributions" to the UN and called for adopting a gradual formula for the reform of the UN Security Council. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   And he met with leaders of some developing countries and asked them to support Japan's "hope" to become permanent membership of the security council and its stand toward the UN reform. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Meanwhile, Japanese diplomats and bureaucrats have visited many countries and asked them to vote for Japan's bid to take a permanent seat on the UNSC in return for "aid" and went the length of "threatening" the UN to cut financial expenditure if it does not give a permanent seat. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   This is a despicable act aimed to buy the permanent seat of the UNSC with money, the commentary notes, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Permanent membership of the UNSC is the responsible position that should adopt fair decisions on behalf of the interests of all regions and countries around the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   It is preposterous that such a country as Japan, which committed crimes unprecedented in human history and has not yet settled it even at the turn of century, becomes a permanent member of the UNSC. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   It is too impudent behaviour making a mockery of the international community and human conscience that Japan attempts to take a responsible UN position with a few money. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Japan should abandon its way of thinking that money decides everything. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   If Japan wants to be a full-fledged member of the international community it should act with discretion, mindful what it should do.

Preparatory committees formed abroad 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 19 (KCNA) -- Preparatory committees were inaugurated in Thailand and Uganda to celebrate the 55th anniversary of the Worker's Party of Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   At an inaugural meeting held in Bangkok on Sept. 12 Krasae Chanawongse, director of the board of the International Institute of the Juche Idea, was elected chairman of the committee. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The committee decided to hold various functions such as a lecture meeting, a rally and a seminar to celebrate the anniversary. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   At an inaugural meeting held in Kampala on Sept. 11 the chairman of the Kampala city committee of the National Movement of Uganda was elected chairman of the national preparatory committee. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The committee set a month of celebrations from Sept. 11 to Oct. 10 and decided to organize a meeting, seminar, lecture meeting and other multifarious functions during the period.
